{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_brookland_ver01/data/sn84026749/00205696398/1930102401/0224.xml":{"full_text":"EDITORIAL PAGE\nOF THE\nBringing Temporary Workers\nHere From the Outside\nTh* long established policy of the Civil Service Commission\nhas been to give temporary positions in the civil service here\nto Washington or nearby people, mainly for the reason that\nwhen dismissed they return to their families no worse off\nfinancially than they were before.\nThe commission will hereafter fill these positions with out*\nside eligible#; at least they are to have preference over Dis\ntrict of Columbia people on the eligible lists.\n1 II I\nIt does hot seem to be a question of apportionment under\nthe civil service laws, because temporary positions are not\nunder the apportionment policies applying to permanent\npositions.\nThere seems to be a desire to give the unemployed away\nfrom Washington opportunities to have work of even short\nduration, unmindful of what may happen when employment\nperiods are iended; unmindful of transportation and other\ncosts; and unmindful of the fact that many of these workers,\nwhen dismissed, will be among the unemployed of Washing\nton unless they are able to return to their homes.\nSome of these people may get permanent positions, depend\ning upon whether the States they come from do not have their\nquotas of workers in the civil service, but most of them will\nnot be cared for in this way.\nIt is hard to believe there are political motives back of this\nnew policy, but it is hard to understand when it is known\nthat there are large numbers of civil service eligible# living\nlh Washington who have lost their positions through cutting\ndown of forces or other causes and are eagerly waiting op\nportunities for replacement in the service.\nThe fair thing would be to give those long waiting for re\nemployment whatever opportunities arise in positions rather\nthan bring outsiders to Washington to be laid off.\nWhy shouldn\u2019t there be consideration for the unemployed\nOs Washington who have civil service status and whose ex\nperience is worth something to the Government?\nDeadly Monoxide Gas\nThe winter toll of deaths from monoxide gas poisoning has\nbegun. Lessons of the past are forgotten by owners of auto\nmobiles.\nClosed, unventilated garages, with auto engines running,\nare veritable death traps. The deadly fumes of monoxide\ngas do their work quickly.\nIven where deaths do not result the fumes are moet danger\nous. Their inhalation cause internal disturbances that often\nincapacitate victims for life.\nNever remain jn a closed garage with an engine running.\nThere are grave dangers when garage doors are open. Never\ngo under a machine to make repairs while the engine is\nrunning, even in the open air.\nThe Autogiro\nWe live today in an era of\nfrantic mechanical experimen\ntation, and we have grown so\naccustomed to miracles that\nnothing seems to surprise us.\nDuring the past half century\nor less, hundreds of types of\naircraft have been invented;\nand many new types are in\ncourse of development and con\nstruction at the present time.\nTwo types of airplanes are\ngreatly needed at the present\ntime. One is the large multi\nmotored plane, of the DO-X\nmodel or type, designed to\ncarry a great amount of fuel\nand scores of passengers, for\ntransoceanic flight. The other\nis a small, safe, inexpensive\nsingle-passenger plane for com\nmon use. It is claimed that\nthe latter has been found at\nlast in the extraordinary air\ncraft known as the autogiro,\nthe invention of Juan de la\nClerva, inventor, sportsman,\nand daring flier.\nThis Interesting Spaniard, a\n.friend of the King of Spain,\nhas been interested in flying\never since he was a lad. At\nthe age of 15, he and his\nbrother made two gliders\nwhich went all right at first.\nBut finally his brother cracked\nup in one of them\u2014and after\nthat, gliders were \"out.\u201d Fol\nlowing this experience, Juan\nmade many planes, the most\nnotable being-the first Spanish\nplane, built in 1911. Eight\nyears later, Cierva had high\nhopes of a tri-motored ship oi\nhis own construction but it\nsmashed, much to his disgust\nand disappointment.\nThe autogiro dates from 1920,\nthe year in which Cierva con\nceived the giro principle. This\nHearst Papers Advocate\n1. \"Peace and amity with all nations; entangling\nalliances with none,\u201d as advocated by George Wash\nington.\n2. Proportional representation in the United States\nSenate, no state to have less than two Senators.\nLegislation to enforce prompt constitutional reap\nportionment in the House of Representatives.\n3. A separate Department of the Army, 'ofa the Navy\nand of the Air Forces, all united under a Secre\ntary of National Defense.\n4. Federal action to the limit of Federal powers to\nabolish illiteracy in the United States under a\nSecretary of Education.\n5. Installation of the President on the first of Jan\nuary following November election.\nSelective immigration to admit only those suited\nfor American citizenship.\nI\n7. Deportation of undesirable aliens.\n8. Complete publicity for income taxes.\nBy Archibald Henderson\nwas something brand new in\naircraft construction, and was\nslow in reaching completion.\nAfter three years of experimen\ntation in making the machine,\nwhich was of simple but flimsy\nconstruction, Cierva finally\nmade a successful flight in\none. During the past seven\nyears, Cierva has been engaged\nin perfecting this machine; and\nit Is expected that, in the near\nfuture, the autogiro will be\nmanufactured in large quanties.\nThe autogiro is a queer ma\nchine in appearance, but it pos\nsesses several features of ex\ntraordinary interest and value.\nThe present two-seater, built\nat the A. V. Roe works, South\nampton, has-a maximum speed\nof 95 miles an hour. It car\nries a Genet-Major 100-horse\npower engine.\nWhen the engine is cut off.\nthe forward motion ceases, and\nthe machine begins to drop to\nwards are ground, at the rate\nof 13 feet per second. Os all\nairplanes, it is able to land\nsafest. It is possible to fly as\nlow as five feet above the level\nof the ground with entire\nsafety. In landing, the pilot\nelevates the tail just before\nreaching the earth. Hie nose\nof the autogiro tips up, the\ntail skid touches ground, and\nthe wheels of the gear come\ninto action. The autogiro may\nbe landed almost anywhere;\nand once landed, it stays put.\nThis curious machine has a\nbiplane tall: two horizontal\nstabilizers, the upper one mov\nable, the lower one fixed. A\nvertical stabilizer and rudder\nare placed at each end of the\nbiplane.\nWA S HJNJSXQU, TIMES\nContempt of Court By T. E. Powers\nf WMT JX\u00bb Vou) (LETHMGok\nLEFT Tub RAT lu. x\nI r ar x\n'(OU R. WHILE.: y I'l} X. 1 I W\nAU O $B\nSO\u00ae \u00aewi\nhr CX\nmJ PT op\nf OfFicttUi z X COURT 9\nacting ouetfiY \"yr\n15?\nI\n\nLetters to the Editor From Readers of The Times\nCivic Benefits of Forum\nDebates Shown by Gale\nEditor, Times:\nYour editorial, \u201cWashington\u2019s\nOpen Forums of Community\nLife,\u201d is timeiy and helpful.\nIt is true, as you say, that\nthe spread of the open-forum\nmovement is a sign of prog\nress and that organizations de\nvoted to frank, fearless but\nwell-ordered discussion of pub\nlic questions are highly valu\nable from a civic standpoint.\nYour indorsement of the open\nforum principle is especially ap\npreciated by me in my capacity\nas president of the Washington\nOpen Forum. I am sure that\nothers active, either in this or\nganization or in groups en\ngaged in similar work, will\nagree with me in commending\nyour stand.\nThe Washington Open Forum,\nunlike local forums designed for\ndefinite sections of the city,\nand unlike forums conducted\nby societies committed to par\nticular policies or doctrines,\naims to be city-wide and neu\ntral. It is not tied to any\ncreed or platform\u2014not even my\nown or that of any other of\nficial or member. Radicals, lib\nerals, conservatives, champions\nof popular opinions and of un\npopular opinions, spokesmen\nfor majority and for minority\nelements, have their turn in it.\nThe speaker one Sunday after\nnoon at our meeting may be a\nstandpat Republican, at another\na Marxian Communist, at an\nother an Al Smith Democrat,\nand so on. Catholic, Jew, Prot\nestant, agnostic and atheist\nlikewise receive fair and cour\nteous .consideration.\nThomas Jefferson said: \u201cEr\nror Is harmless when reason is\nleft free to commit it.\u201d Vol\ntaire declared: \u201cI disagree with\nwhat you say, but I will fight\nto the death for your rignt\nto say it.\u201d These two state\nments epitomize the open\nforum principle. They are sane\nand salutary expressions of a\nmighty truth.\nThree United States Senators,\none Representative, one judge,\none Federal radio commissioner,\nclergymen, heretics, 100 percent\ners, war resistors, wets, drys,\nfeminists and anti-feminists have\noccupied our rostrum In the\npast couple of years. All of\nthem have commended us for\nour fairness and orderly pro\ncedure. Every Sunday we con\nduct public lectures at 3 p. m.\nat 808 Eye St. N. W. Wash\nington people\u2014and visitors in\nour city, as well\u2014are cordially\ninvited to be present.\nLINN A. E. GALE.\nTraction 12-Hour Day\nDenounced by Visitor\nEditor, Times:\nWhen in your city, I was sur\nprised to hear that your street\nrailway companies are now get\nting a 10-cent fare.\nI made inquiries and found\nthat no wages were increased,\nbut the big surprise was to hear\nthat they are still working\nmany of their men 12 hours per\nday, every da>. including Sun\ndays. the hours Ijung from I\na. m. to 8 p. m. Pardon me,\nthey do. give them ONE day off\nonce in every month.\nI was wondering how many\nof the officials of the company\nrealize these men work 12 hours\na day. What do you suppose\nwould happen if the officials,\nfrom the president down, were\nasked to work 12 hours a day?\nNo doubt there would be a\nquick change made in the\nworking hours. Poor men! I\ncan only say you need another\nAbraham I Lincoln to set you\nfree.\nJ. M. ANDERSON.\nListen, World!\nAn hour ago the light was\nclanging brass;\nThe yellow earth sprawled flat\nalong the rocks\nLike some great cat, half dead\nfrom heat and thirst;\nThe trees stood scorched and\nrigid, drowned in glare.\nNow suddenly, across the brazen\nsky,\nAcross the miles of tortured,\ntwanging air,\nThere spreads a shadow, like\na stilling hand\nAnd in the hush the earth be\ngins to move,\nFlex its great muscles, softly\ncome alive.\nThe dust glows pink as newly\nwakened flesh;\nLike sap the color floods the\nwithered trees;\nThe grasses gild\u2014and, from the\nchapparal,\nThere comes a scent of apples,\npitch and spice,\nAnd tiny voices in a web of\nsound.\nThe sky, that was as white as\nbleaching bone\nIs quickened now with a warm,\nflooding tide\nOs pearl and coral, rose and\napricot\nThat spreads and spills until the\nvalley brims\nWith pools of honey and the\ngullies stream j\nWith shadows, darky purple as\nnew wine.\nTo north, to south, the long\nSierra heaves\nIts black-troughed ridges, bronze\nagainst the gold.\nAnd from the tumbled crests\nthere spurts a spray\nOs fiery spindrift over saffron\nsurf.\nFountains of crimson spurting\nscarlet spray.\nSomewhere within this welter\nwhirls the sun\nHalf lost beneath the roaring\nsurf of flame.\nMolten, enormous drop ping\ndown and down.\nUntil, with one last flare, its\nblaze is gone;\nAnd, in the east, between the\ntall, black files\nOs bull pines, gleams a band of\ngreen,\nClear as thin jade\u2014like one.\nhigh, singing note.\nAnd now, as suddenly as fire\n\u2022wept\nMarried Woman Raps\nMary Garden's Idea\nEditor, Times:\nI do not know just what this\nletter will do or how far it will\nget; it may land in the waste\nbasket. Nevertheless, I will get\nit out of my system.\nIn regard to a paragraph by\nMary Garden in the Times, it\nsure did make my blood boil\nto read what she says about\nmarried women being lazy.\nWell, I surely would think of\nRobinson\nBy Elsie\nIn pulsing waves across the\nashen sky.\nSd suddenly the brightness ebbs\nand cools;\nOnce more the sky is white,\nbut now with space;\nLike smoke the mountains\ncrumble and the rocks dis\nsolve,\nAnd there is silence where the\ncolor sang.\nWhite sky-blue silence, sifting\nsoft as snow\u2014\nThe woosh of owl wings a\ncoyote\u2019s howl\u2014\nThe tiny, squeaking flutter of a\nbat\u2014\nThen once more silence \u2014and\nabove the peak\nOne great star kindles, signal\ning the night.\n(Copyright, 19.10, by King Feature!\nSyndicate, Inc.)\nKNOWLEDGE\nTEST\nFill each blank:\n1. Ascot is famous for\nits\n2. The cobra is a very veno\nmous\n3. The moon is a of\nthe earth.\n4. A rotunda is a large\nroom.\n5. A shilling is a sil-\nver coin.\nDo you know:\n6. What King of England\ncommanded the tides to go\nback?\n7. What is the Southern\nCross?\n8. What is the only State\nnamed for a President?\n9. In whose Presidency was\nCalifornia admitted to the\nUnion?\n10. From what play of\nShakespeare comes the line,\n\"Life is but a walking shadow\u201d?\nMatch correctly:\n11. freight\nderide\n12. ridicule\nopulent\n13. wealthy\ncargo\n14. gaunt\nsavage\n15. brutal\nhaggard\nlipaww Magadne PagaJ\nlady of Mary Garden\u2019s intelli\ngence certainly would know\nbetter.\nI am married, a mother of\ntwo fine daughters, and really\nthink I am more Important\nthan she. How could she make\nsuch a statement? It really is\nabsurd.\nWhat she says is bosh. A\nwoman that has a family has\nto work and the married wives\nwho work in the world surely\nare not loafing by any means.\nMost married women have to\nwork to live in these hard\ntimes.\nI really think we are more\nthan she is. How\nAbout it, married women?\nW. F. S.\nSECRETS OF~\nHEALTH\n\u2014By Dr. Louis E. Bisch\u2014\nAre you a sufferer from\n\u201cmorning grouch\u201d?\nWell, there surely are thou\nsands of men who \u201cget out\nof the wrong side of the bed.\u201d\nOn awakening they are cross\nand irritable. They don\u2019t make\nvery agreeable breakfast com\npanions. Sometimes the grouch\npersists until they reach the\noffice and then business as\nsociates suffer as well as the\nwife and children at home.\nI don\u2019t suppose all men are\nthat way. Nor all women.\nBut certainly more men behave\nthat way than women.\nTo be \"grouchy\u201d upon wak\ning has several reasons behind\nit. On the psychological side\nit is a protest against being\ndisturbed!\nIt Indicates a distaste of\nfacing the realities of life!\nThe person who habitually\noversleeps is a case in point.\nHe doesn\u2019t like the tasks of\nlife and he doesn\u2019t want to\nget started.\nHis subconscious mind pro\ntects him against the unpleas\nant experiences which he knows\nhe has to endure. It wraps him\nin the arms of Morpheus and\nlulls him into a sense of se\ncurity. \u201cCure-charming Sleep,\nthou easer of all woes.\u201d\nAnd why are women less\nlikely to be bad-tempered in the\nmornings than men?\nBecause women are more\nadaptable than men. Women\ncan make the best of things\nwith finer grace than men.\nWomen are more likely to ac\ncept them than to rebel.\nWomen are more reasonable\nand practical when it comes to\nresigning to the inevitable.\nThe feeling of safety that\nsleep engenders probably goes\nback to the days before we were\nactually bom. The mind func\ntioned to some degrees at least\nat that time. Perhaps it got\nthe notion that sleep, security\nand freedom from annoyance\nexpressed identical states of\nwell-being.\nWhen a child is bom it cries.\nThere may be a psychological\nsignificance in that, besides the\nphysiological one of exercising\ntb\u00ab luDia ta to taMttak\nSpeeding Prosperity Return\nNew York Joins Nation in a Vast Program. By Spending\nWisely, You Too Can Help.\niS&R\nIN I\nEVER\\ I\nSjRE? LINE I\nzNoW IS THe.*TIKG.*To\nDoWN <hTo *THt SOCK*\nBuV\nPresident Hoover names a special Cabinet Committee to\npush Federal building projects and to join with the States in\nhastening construction on all public works.\n\u201cWe must find jobs for the unemployed,\" says the\nPresident in effect; \"We must keep those of our citizens\nwho are in honest difficulties from suffering from hunger\nand cold.\"\nIn New York State, Governor Boosevelt is spending as\nrapidly as possible the balance of the State\u2019s appropriation\nfor needed improvements, with the purpose of increasing the\nnumber of jobs for the jobless.\nIn New York City the Board of Estimate adds a million\ndollars to the budget for the relief of unemployment.\nAll of these are splendid, constructive efforts to speed the\nreturn of prosperity.\nYou, too, can aid the return of prosperity, if you have a job\nand an income, by wise SPENDING.\nYou will do business a favor and you will do yourself a\nfavor.\nThere are times and seasons for saving, and times and\nseasons for spending.\nThe time for saving is when prices are high, when your\ndollar will buy comparatively little.\nThe time for spending is when prices are low, when your\ndollar buys much.\nJust now prices are low indeed\u2014probably as low as they\nwill ever be. Your dollar will buy nearly twice what it would\na year ago.\nAt such times, hoarding is foolish. All great fortunes were\nfounded in times of depression. You may not expect to found\na great fortune, but you can buy with profit the necessities\nand even some of the luxuries that you want now or later.\nYou are not advised to waste your money. But under certain\nconditions, failure to spend can be truly called WASTE.\nThose conditions prevail now. If you have saved money in\nprevious years, when there was a lot of it lying around loose,\nyou should CASH IN on your prudence.\nThere are bargain days in every line. They will not last\nforever.\nAre You a Dionysian?\nOr an Appollonian!\nModern psychology, prying into your brain and character,\ntells you that you are either a Dionysian or an Appollonian.\nPerhaps you did not know that.\nA Dionysian is emotional or even hysterical, and is inclined to\nbe more interested in things outside him than those inside.\nAn Appollonian is intellectual, has a strong sense of duty,\nand is more interested in his own personality tiAn in external\nmatters.\nMost of us are part Dionysian and part Appollonian, but each\nof ns is more one than the other.\nThe majority of Americans, as analysed by Dr. Frits Wittels,\nnoted Viennese psychologist now in this country, are Appollo\nnians. 1\nAs Dr. Wittels puts it:\n\"TAe American is apt to be overweighted with a\nsense of duty that he must do something to justify\nhis existence and to maintain his self-respect.\n\u201cThis is a tremendous force, that makes you live\naccording to rules and makes you do things that you\ndon\u2019t want to do. It also compels you to deny your\nself things you desire. Denying yourself leads, in\nturn, to a feeling of self-righteousness which makes\nyou want to impose your sense of compulsion on\nothers, to force them to deny themselves things they\ndesire.\n\u201cProhibition is a very good example of the result\ndf this \u2019neurosis\u2019.\u201d\nHowever, America has plenty of Dionysians, also, if Dr. Wit\ntels is right. He goes on:\n\u201cThe Dionysian is the opposite in every respect of\nthe Appollonian. His is the temperament whose\nmotto is \u2019Live and let live,\u2019 or \u2019Eat, drink and he\nmerry, for tomorrow is another day, and today is as\nwell worth while as tomorrow.\u2019 He is enthusiastic,\nexuberant, full of the joy of living, a pagan and a\nspendthrift, easy going and generous, who would\ngive away everything he has so that others may also\nenjoy themselves. Unfortunately, by his very nature\nhe is not of the thrifty kind, and hence has little\nworldly wealth at his command. The rich are gen\nerally Appollonians.\n\u201cThe Appollonian says: \u2019You must do as say or\nI will punish you.\u2019 The Dionysian says: \u2019l\u2019ll always\nlove you, no matter what you do\n\u201cThe one believes in coercion, the other in\nfreedom.\u201d\nDr. Wittels\u2019 illuminating ideas explain much that is going on\nnow in America\u2014prohibition, blue laws, capital punishment, on\nthe one hand; and nervous breakdowns, divorce, drunkenness\nand Earl Carroll shows on the other.\nIf Puritan fanatics and free-love pagans had themselves ana\nlyzed, each might learn something.\nYou, neither a fanatic nor a pagan, may be interested in ana\nlyzing YOUMELF. You will find it instructive to know\nwhether you are an Appollonian or a Dionysian\u2014and how much.\n.WASHINGTON, D. G,\nOCTOBER 24,1930","height":"30476","width":"24356"}}
